fields.description:
The ELB returns four timing metrics through the access log.

request_processing_time
backend_processing_time
response_processing_time
latency

These metrics are provided by haproxy timings. The values that we return are valid for the request, but, do not match the intention of the timings reported by AWS access logs.

I have discussed this with Sang-Min who agrees with my assessment and has asked that I capture them in a EUCA.

*Backend_processing_time – we seem to be on the same page here with AWS*
 
Amazon Definition: “The total time elapsed, in seconds, from the time the load balancer sent the request to a registered instance until the instance started to send the response headers.”
 
Eucalyptus Definition (haproxy log value tr): “total time in milliseconds spent waiting for the server [registered instance?] to send a full HTTP response, not counting data”
 
*Request_processing_time – I don’t think we’re capturing as much as AWS here*
 
Amazon Definition: "The total time elapsed, in seconds, from the time the load balancer received the request until the time it sent it to a registered instance."
 
Eucalyptus Definition (haproxy log value tw): "total time spent in the queues waiting for a connection slot. It accounts for listener's queue as well as the server's queue, and depends on the queue size, and the time needed for the server to complete previous"
 
I think to match AWS we would need to combine tw+tc
 
Tc is defined as “total time in ms spent waiting for the connection to establish to the final server, including retries”
 
*Response_processing_time – We don’t return a value other than -1 here*
 
Amazon Definition: "The total time elapsed (in seconds) from the time the load balancer received the response header from the registered instance until it started to send the response to the client. This includes both the queuing time at the load balancer and the connection acquisition time from the load balancer to the back end."
 
Eucalyptus Definiton: We respond with -1 in all cases
 
We have tt available which is the full timing of the request/response, we could return

tt - (tq + tw + tc +tr) 

This would give us an approximation of the amazon result, although this may not match a similar request to amazon it would give us an additional metric that is not currently returned and would be an improvement over '-1'
 
*Latency (cloudwatch only) – We seem to differ totally from AWS here* 

Amazon Definition: "The time elapsed, in seconds, after the request leaves the load balancer until the headers of the response are received."
 
Eucalyptus Definition (haproxy log value tt): “total time in milliseconds elapsed between the accept and the last close. It covers all possible processings”
 
We should return 'tr' here for cloudwatch which is the 'backend_processing_time' value that also appears in the logs.

comments.body:
Two metrics that we need to fix in 4.4 are <Request_processing_time> and <Latency>. The latency metric may still have an issue with HTTP POST, as illustrated in this SO thread: http://stackoverflow.com/questions/25712966/understanding-aws-elb-latency. Still it will be the better estimate than what we have currently.

I don' think we can address <Response_processing_time>. I would prefer a value not available than presenting a potentially inaccurate one.
I vote approval for making the change in 4.3.1.

To help verify the fix, these are the steps that I used to manually test:

1) Run instances and install apache2

2) Prepare for moderately sized index.html. I used the one from yahoo.com:
   curl https://www.yahoo.com/ --insecure > /var/www/index.html 

3) Update the default apache.conf so that it slows down the server (If we don't, all metrics reported will be 0 because the server is too fast). ThreadsPerChild and MaxClients are reduced to 2.


{code:java}
<IfModule mpm_prefork_module>
    StartServers          5
    MinSpareServers       5
    MaxSpareServers      10
    ThreadsPerChild     2
    MaxClients          2
    MaxRequestsPerChild   0
</IfModule>

<IfModule mpm_worker_module>
    StartServers          2
    MinSpareThreads      25
    MaxSpareThreads      75
    ThreadLimit          64
    ThreadsPerChild      2
    MaxClients          2
    MaxRequestsPerChild   0
</IfModule>
{code}

4) Create a new loadbalancer with http:80 as front-end and back-end protocol and port. Register the apache instance with it. Wait until the registered instances become InService. 

5) Enable access log for the loadbalancer, by following https://docs.eucalyptus.com/eucalyptus/4.3.0/#user-guide/elb_examples_access_logs.html. 
To create a bucket and change its access control, I used awscli:
 
{code:java}
 aws s3 --endpoint-url http://s3.c-35.autoqa.qa1.eucalyptus-systems.com:8773/ mb s3://accesslog
  aws s3api --endpoint-url http://s3.c-35.autoqa.qa1.eucalyptus-systems.com:8773/  put-bucket-acl --grant-write "id=000006093726" --bucket accesslog
{code}

5) Use 'ab' to generate enough traffic against the loadbalancer. Note the concurrency is set to 50 so that the small number of threads in the server would block the request. 

ab -n 1000000 -c 50 -s 30 http://securelb2-000168793355.lb.c-35.autoqa.qa1.eucalyptus-systems.com/

6) Wait for a few minutes. Then use euwatch to check the cloudwatch latency:
euwatch-get-stats -n AWS/ELB --dimensions LoadBalancerName=securelb2 -s Average --period 60 --start-time "2016-11-02T00:00:00Z" --end-time "2016-11-03T00:00:00Z" Latency
The expected latency is between 0.1 to 1 seconds.

7) Download access log from s3:
{code:java}
  aws s3 --endpoint-url http://s3.c-35.autoqa.qa1.eucalyptus-systems.com:8773/ cp s3://accesslog/AWSLogs/000168793355/elasticloadbalancing/eucalyptus/2016/11/1/000168793355_elasticloadbalancing_eucalyptus_securelb2_20161101T2220Z_0.0.0.0_4rf3jpmc.log ./
{code}

Make sure "request_processing_time" and "backend_processing_time" fields are filled with a number (>=0). "response_processing_time" field is still filled with '-1'. 
http://docs.aws.amazon.com/elasticloadbalancing/latest/classic/access-log-collection.html
